---
import HomeLayout from "../../layouts/HomeLayout.astro";
import "../../styles/content.css";

const weekplan = [
  {
    day: "Day 1",
    what: "Understand the brief. The agent helps your child figure out their country, committee, and what's actually being asked.",
  },
  {
    day: "Day 2",
    what: "Find the arguments. Research turns into two or three clear positions, each backed by a real fact.",
  },
  {
    day: "Day 3",
    what: "Draft the position paper — properly structured: background, stance, and proposed solutions.",
  },
  {
    day: "Day 4",
    what: "Cut it to the word limit. Your child learns to say the same thing in fewer, sharper words.",
  },
  {
    day: "Day 5",
    what: "Write the opening speech. One minute, one message, said with confidence.",
  },
  {
    day: "Day 6",
    what: "Practise out loud. Pace, pauses, and eye contact — rehearsed, not winged.",
  },
  {
    day: "Day 7",
    what: "Full rehearsal, then a report for you: what's ready, and what still needs a little work.",
  },
];

const url = "https://1quest.app/school/extracurricular-assignments/";
const title =
  "Model UN, Essays, Debates & Demonstrations: Helping Your Child Prepare | 1Quest";
const description =
  "Schools ask for Model UN papers, speeches, debates, and demonstrations — each needing a different skill. Here's how 1Quest patiently teaches your child, locks a plan with you, and executes it over a week.";
const datePublished = "2026-07-05";
const dateModified = "2026-07-05";

const articleSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  headline: "Model UN, essays, debates, demonstrations — and one calm way through them all.",
  description,
  datePublished,
  dateModified,
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
  image: "https://1quest.app/og-image.png",
  author: { "@type": "Organization", name: "1Quest", url: "https://1quest.app/" },
  publisher: {
    "@type": "Organization",
    name: "1Quest",
    logo: { "@type": "ImageObject", url: "https://1quest.app/logo-512.png" },
  },
};

const breadcrumb = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
  itemListElement: [
    { "@type": "ListItem", position: 1, name: "Home", item: "https://1quest.app/" },
    {
      "@type": "ListItem",
      position: 2,
      name: "School guides",
      item: "https://1quest.app/school/",
    },
    { "@type": "ListItem", position: 3, name: "Model UN, essays, debates & demonstrations", item: url },
  ],
};
---

<HomeLayout title={title} description={description} jsonLd={[articleSchema, breadcrumb]}>
  <article class="article">
    <header class="article__header">
      <div class="wrap-read">
        <p class="eyebrow">1Quest for School · Guide</p>
        <h1 class="article__title">
          Model UN, essays, debates, demonstrations — and one calm way through them all.
        </h1>
        <p class="article__meta">For parents · 6 min read</p>
        <p class="article__lead">
          Schools ask for far more than tests now. Here's how to help your child prepare for
          the endless variety — without becoming an expert in all of it yourself.
        </p>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="wrap-read prose-lg">
      <h2>The assignment isn't the problem. The variety is.</h2>
      <p>
        One week it's a Model UN position paper. The next, a two-minute speech. Then a debate
        rebuttal, a science demonstration, a group presentation, an essay pinned to a strict
        word limit. Every one of them asks for a <strong>different skill</strong> — research,
        structure, delivery, timing, persuasion.
      </p>
      <p>
        No parent is fluent in all of that. And here's the quiet unfairness: your child is
        usually told <em>what</em> to produce, but almost never taught <em>how</em>. So the
        week becomes a scramble — late nights, half-finished slides, and a child who learned to
        survive the task without learning to do the next one any better.
      </p>

      <h2>What your child actually needs is patience, not answers.</h2>
      <p>
        A good tutor for this doesn't hand over a finished speech. They teach your child how to
        build one — and they don't lose patience on the third attempt, or the fifth. That's
        exactly what 1Quest's agents are built to do.
      </p>
      <p>
        Ask for help with a Model UN position and the agent walks your child through it, step by
        step: understand the country, find the arguments, structure the paper, tighten it to the
        word limit. It explains, waits, checks that your child actually followed, and tries
        again as many times as it takes. The skill stays with your child long after the
        assignment is handed in.
      </p>
      <div class="callout">
        <p>The goal isn't a better assignment this week. It's a child who can do the next one on their own.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>You lock a plan with 1Quest in minutes.</h2>
      <p>
        You know the deadline and the brief. What you don't have is the hours to run the prep
        yourself. So you don't have to.
      </p>
      <p>
        Log in as a parent and simply tell the agent what's due: <em>“She has a Model UN
        conference in a week — a position paper and a one-minute opening speech.”</em> In a short
        back-and-forth you agree on a plan — what your child will do each day, how long it should
        take, and what “finished” looks like. You set it once, and you don't have to chase it.
      </p>

      <h2>Then it works with your child, a little each day.</h2>
      <p>
        Over the week, the agent sits with your child and quietly executes the plan — in small
        sessions that fit around school, never crammed into one panicked night. Here's what a
        Model UN week can look like:
      </p>
      <ul class="weekplan">
        {
          weekplan.map((d) => (
            <li>
              <span class="weekplan__day">{d.day}</span>
              <span class="weekplan__what">{d.what}</span>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
      <p>
        Each day builds on the last. Your child is learning the craft <em>while</em> producing
        the work — which is the whole point.
      </p>

      <h2>And at the end, it reports back to you.</h2>
      <p>
        When the week is done — or any time you ask — you get a clear picture: what your child
        finished, where they did well, and where they struggled. Maybe the research was strong
        but the speech ran long. You'll know, and so will the agent, which quietly focuses on
        that next time.
      </p>
      <p>
        It's one plan with two views. Your child sees encouragement and the next small step; you
        see honest progress. <strong>Same path — it just knows who it's talking to.</strong>
      </p>

      <h2>Start with one assignment.</h2>
      <p>
        Pick the next thing on your child's calendar — a debate, a demonstration, an essay — and
        let 1Quest run it with them this week. You'll both feel the difference by the weekend.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <section class="closing">
    <div class="shell closing__inner">
      <h2 class="closing__title">Bring a patient tutor to your child's next assignment.</h2>
      <p class="closing__sub">
        Free to start. Tell 1Quest what's due, agree on a plan, and let it do the patient part.
      </p>
      <a class="btn btn--solid" href="/contact/">Start free</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</HomeLayout>
